              "explanation": "A QTc &gt;500ms represents a clinically significant threshold associated with substantially increased risk of torsades de pointes (TdP), a potentially fatal ventricular arrhythmia. At this threshold: reassess whether the QTc-prolonging medication is necessary, correct hypokalemia and hypomagnesemia (electrolytes potentiate QTc risk), and consider cardiology consultation. QTc 440-500ms is borderline — avoid adding more QTc-prolonging agents."
