          "clinicalPearls": [
            "Quetiapine's sedation comes primarily from H1 and α1 blockade — not D2 — which is why low doses (25-100 mg) are sedating without antipsychotic efficacy.",
            "FDA-approved for schizophrenia, bipolar I mania, bipolar depression, and as an adjunct for major depression.",
            "Quetiapine (especially XR) is one of the better-studied antipsychotics for bipolar depression — an indication where most antipsychotics lack robust evidence.",
            "Off-label use for insomnia is common but controversial; low doses don't give antipsychotic benefit but do carry metabolic risks.",
            "Metabolic risk is moderate-to-high — monitor weight, glucose, and lipids at baseline and every 3 months.",
            "QTc prolongation risk is present — check ECG at baseline and when doses are high or other QT-prolonging agents are added."
          ],
