              "content": "## Metabolic Risk Rankings\n\n| Risk Level | Antipsychotics |\n|---|---|\n| **Highest** | Clozapine, Olanzapine |\n| **High** | Quetiapine, Iloperidone |\n| **Moderate** | Paliperidone, Risperidone |\n| **Low-Moderate** | Haloperidol, Asenapine, Chlorpromazine |\n| **Lowest** | Aripiprazole, Ziprasidone, Lurasidone |\n\n## Monitoring Protocol (APA Guidelines)\n\n| Parameter | Baseline | 4 wks | 8 wks | 12 wks | Quarterly | Annually |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Weight/BMI | ✓ | ✓ | ✓ | ✓ | ✓ | — |\n| Waist circumference | ✓ | — | — | ✓ | — | ✓ |\n| Blood pressure | ✓ | — | — | ✓ | — | ✓ |\n| Fasting glucose | ✓ | — | — | ✓ | — | ✓ |\n| Fasting lipids | ✓ | — | — | ✓ | — | ✓ |\n| HbA1c | ✓ | — | — | — | — | ✓ |\n\n## Evidence-Based Interventions\n\n### Metformin\n- Most evidence-based pharmacological intervention for antipsychotic-induced weight gain\n- Dose: 500 mg BID, may titrate to 1000 mg BID\n- Reduces weight, improves insulin sensitivity\n- Consider starting concurrently with high-risk antipsychotics (don't wait for gain to occur)\n\n### GLP-1 Receptor Agonists\n- Semaglutide (Ozempic/Wegovy), liraglutide (Victoza/Saxenda)\n- Emerging evidence in antipsychotic-induced obesity\n- Consider when metformin is insufficient or not tolerated\n\n### Antipsychotic Switching\n- Switch to metabolically neutral agent if: weight gain ≥7% baseline, HbA1c >6.5%, new dyslipidemia\n- Options: aripiprazole, ziprasidone, lurasidone\n\n### Lifestyle Intervention\n- Structured programs combining diet, exercise, and behavioral counseling\n- Can prevent 2-3 kg weight gain if started early\n- Should be offered to ALL patients starting antipsychotics"
