              "id": "sec-bupropion-overview",
              "title": "Bupropion: Mechanism & Clinical Profile",
              "type": "text",
              "content": "## Mechanism of Action\n\nBupropion is a **norepinephrine-dopamine reuptake inhibitor (NDRI)**:\n- Blocks NET (norepinephrine transporter)\n- Blocks DAT (dopamine transporter)\n- **No serotonergic activity** — the key distinguishing feature\n- Weak nicotinic acetylcholine receptor antagonism — contributes to smoking cessation efficacy\n\n## Formulations\n\n| Formulation | Dosing | Notes |\n|---|---|---|\n| Wellbutrin IR | 100-150 mg TID | Higher seizure risk per dose; largely replaced |\n| Wellbutrin SR | 150-200 mg BID | Standard release; 8-hour dosing |\n| Wellbutrin XL | 300-450 mg QAM | Most prescribed; once daily |\n| Forfivo XL | 450 mg QAM | Single pill for high-dose regimen |\n| Zyban | 150 mg SR BID | Smoking cessation branding |\n\n## FDA-Approved Indications\n\n- Major depressive disorder\n- Seasonal affective disorder (SAD) — preventive use before winter season\n- Smoking cessation (as Zyban)\n\n## Advantages Over SSRIs\n\n- **Weight-neutral or weight loss**: Due to dopaminergic/noradrenergic activity on appetite regulation\n- **No sexual side effects**: No serotonergic activity → no serotonin-mediated sexual dysfunction\n- **Activating/energizing**: Beneficial for fatigue, hypersomnia, anhedonia\n- **ADHD benefit**: Off-label evidence for adult ADHD (second-line after stimulants)\n\n## Contraindications\n\n- **Eating disorders** (anorexia nervosa, bulimia nervosa) — 3-4× elevated seizure risk due to electrolyte imbalances\n- **Seizure disorder** or history of head trauma with seizure risk\n- **Abrupt discontinuation** of alcohol, benzodiazepines, barbiturates, or anticonvulsants\n- **MAOIs** within 14 days (serotonin/dopamine interaction risk)\n- **Linezolid or IV methylene blue** (MAOI properties)\n\n## Seizure Risk\n\n- At doses ≤450 mg/day: seizure risk ~0.1% (equivalent to other antidepressants)\n- Risk increases non-linearly above 450 mg/day — do NOT exceed\n- IR formulation has higher peak-dose seizure risk → SR/XL formulations preferred"
