              "explanation": "In patients with liver disease, lorazepam (along with oxazepam and temazepam — the 'FOLT' group) is preferred because it undergoes only glucuronidation (phase II metabolism), not phase I hepatic oxidative metabolism. Diazepam and chlordiazepoxide undergo extensive hepatic phase I metabolism, resulting in drug and metabolite accumulation in cirrhosis, increasing encephalopathy and over-sedation risk. Alprazolam's short half-life makes it problematic for withdrawal management."
