              "id": "sec-sleep-overview",
              "title": "Pharmacological Approaches to Insomnia",
              "type": "table",
              "content": "## CBT-I First\nCognitive Behavioral Therapy for Insomnia (CBT-I) is the first-line treatment for chronic insomnia — superior to medications for long-term outcomes.\n\n## Medication Options\n\n| Agent | Class | Mechanism | Cautions |\n|-------|-------|-----------|----------|\n| Zolpidem (Ambien) | Z-drug | GABA-A agonist (non-BZD) | Sleep-driving, amnesia, falls in elderly; Beers Criteria |\n| Eszopiclone (Lunesta) | Z-drug | GABA-A agonist | Metallic taste; Beers Criteria |\n| Zaleplon (Sonata) | Z-drug | Ultra-short (1h half-life) — middle-of-night use | Beers Criteria |\n| Trazodone 25-100mg | Antidepressant | 5-HT2A antagonist, H1 antagonist | Orthostasis, priapism (rare), non-addictive |\n| Doxepin (Silenor) | TCA | H1 antagonist at very low doses (3-6mg) | FDA-approved for insomnia |\n| Suvorexant (Belsomra) | Orexin antagonist | Blocks wake-promoting orexin | FDA-approved; vivid dreams; less dependence risk |\n| Lemborexant (Dayvigo) | Orexin antagonist | Same class as suvorexant | FDA-approved 2019 |\n| Melatonin | Supplement | MT1/MT2 agonist | Circadian rhythm; low side effects |\n| Ramelteon (Rozerem) | Melatonin receptor agonist | MT1/MT2 agonist | No dependence; FDA-approved |\n| Mirtazapine 7.5-15mg | Antidepressant | H1 antagonist (more sedating at low doses) | Weight gain; sedation |\n\n## Beers Criteria — Elderly Caution\nZ-drugs and most benzodiazepines are on the Beers Criteria for older adults — associated with falls, fractures, cognitive impairment, and MVAs. Prefer low-dose doxepin, trazodone, or ramelteon in elderly."
