              "explanation": "This is classic delirium: acute onset (hours to days), fluctuating course, visual hallucinations, disorientation in a patient with a known medical trigger (UTI) and previously intact cognition. Delirium is always secondary to a medical cause — the UTI is the precipitant. Dementia is gradual; new-onset schizophrenia at 80 is vanishingly rare."
